<pageBreakToken id="AAB5B7B33C30CF086207E819C7E0CC71" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" start="start">Type</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9DFEB2FB2E4209A3701E62718D3F9290" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">
EGYPT, Sinai, 
<emphasis id="A9CCF834CA3F3E1FDA225CFC770624FA" italics="true" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Schimper</emphasis>
s.n. (holotype G; isotypes BM!, K!, P!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="91EFFB840AF71481A6D418F2DD44E741" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" type="description">
<paragraph id="B5E3C0DF0C503DEC39C1D60AD3EBB425" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="63FFF00EF552F4C94DC97E211B4DEF34" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">
Perennial herb from a stout woody rootstock to 50 cm in height, all parts covered in long spreading hairs, which are rust-coloured when dry. Basal leaves petiolate, 1.5-6.5 
<normalizedToken id="591A62EDE914B2CF011BDC2715217DE3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-1 cm, obovate or oblanceolate, obtuse, margin strongly undulate, with long petiole-like base; stem leaves sessile, shorter (&lt;2.5 cm long), linear-oblanceolate. Flowers in pedunculate heads with up to 5 flowers; bracts 1-1.5 
<normalizedToken id="5CC6359C467E478C30D052EED30452A8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-0.7 cm, oblong-elliptic; peduncles 0-11 mm long, about equalling the subtending bract; bracteoles 12 
<normalizedToken id="2CF61ACB6516ACC869A5C62ED7F641DC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2 mm, linear-oblanceolate; pedicels absent; outer sepals 10-11 
<normalizedToken id="2BB54CAABD5C14D30A87F63E6FD65827" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3 mm, lanceolate, acute, villous; inner sepals narrower and shorter, c. 8-9 
<normalizedToken id="AC6BBC8911FC5D16F8262DEF0007E889" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1 mm; corolla 2-2.2 cm, colour unknown, wavy at the apex, scarcely lobed, midpetaline bands pilose; ovary and style glabrous divided c. 5 mm above base, stigmas c. 5 mm. Capsule not seen. [
<bibRefCitation id="8501FE0F508C63370114787810DE59BB" author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken id="0D3AB422F664625FC75CE86C16834C76" originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 167; 
<bibRefCitation id="F21757047D34551CF5B1BA6530CFCBFF" author="Boulos, L" journalOrPublisher="Flora of Egypt" pageId="200" pageNumber="201" pagination="242 - 267" refId="B59" refString="Boulos, L, 2000. . Flora of Egypt 2: 242 - 267" volume="2" year="2000">Boulos 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 247]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1BE3D34CF1E12C6BE2873EA66B7758EB" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="4524C9919FC78785105547C04BA52FBD" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="77FABEC1E3CD6ABA26E63513AD30C466" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">
Endemic to Sinai in Egypt (
<emphasis id="88F70C5718F607615EBB3D918D84648F" italics="true" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Holland</emphasis>
s.n., 
<emphasis id="EF69D46B0DD36C07A3C7163E51EB648F" italics="true" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">MacDonald</emphasis>
s.n., 
<emphasis id="F6A142595519829B760F65DEB9D27CB5" italics="true" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Hart</emphasis>
s.n. [1883/4]). Apparently a rare species. Records from Arabia are errors.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D00A6605A78BC2B35D36EA879558C4B8" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" type="notes">
<paragraph id="5A61EF1753BAE739945460FC42D8F836" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0673AC980665C82E2BA390F4E840547E" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">
Distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="1E07FCE30C7E323F3DD45CC057666D29" authorityName="Peter ex Hallier f., Bot. Jahrb. Syst. 18: 99. 1893 [&quot; 1894 &quot;]. (Hallier" authorityYear="1893" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus spicatus" order="Solanales" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spicatus">Convolvulus spicatus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="E63A126018250526D9218C07295BB56B" authorityName="Sa'ad, Meded. Bot. Mus. Herb. Rijks Univ. Utrecht 281: 166. 1967. (Sa'ad" authorityYear="1967" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus jordanensis" order="Solanales" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="jordanensis">
<emphasis id="EAF9AEE8B42F7C1498C0FD2368253344" italics="true" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Convolvulus jordanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the strongly undulate leaves. It is very similar to some forms of 
<taxonomicName id="F55F36BB797FB8A58F29495B5E72BACA" authorityName="Boiss., Diagn. Pl. Orient. 7: 24. 1846. (Boissier" authorityYear="1846" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus cephalopodus" order="Solanales" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cephalopodus">
<emphasis id="0CA5ADEE781B9D8FD51C1ACD582396FE" italics="true" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Convolvulus cephalopodus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but distinguished by the glabrous ovary. It appears to be prostrate like 
<taxonomicName id="43D3A9A57E7C99CB90E298163E988C49" authorityName="Desr., Encycl. [Lamarck et al.] 3: 553. 1792. (Desrousseaux" authorityYear="1792" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus secundus" order="Solanales" pageId="187" pageNumber="188" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="secundus">
<emphasis id="B3813D8DBA6DFCEEC1DD6FFFB8BC64DC" italics="true" pageId="187" pageNumber="188">Convolvulus secundus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is distinguished by the shortly pedunculate heads as well as the distinctive leaves.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
